@page "/"

<PageTitle>About</PageTitle>

<h1>About My Snake Client</h1>

<p>
    This project is a Blazor-based Snake client that connects to the provided Snake server,
    receives world updates, renders the game world, and sends player movement commands.
    My main goal was to build a client that follows the required communication protocol,
    keeps the code organized using MVC, and provides a clear and responsive game view.
</p>

<h2>Design Overview</h2>

<p>
    I structured the project using the MVC pattern required in the handout.
    The <strong>Models</strong> folder contains the data classes used to represent the game state,
    including <code>Snake</code>, <code>Wall</code>, <code>Powerup</code>, <code>Point2D</code>, and <code>World</code>.
    The <strong>Controllers</strong> folder contains the networking logic, especially
    <code>NetworkConnection</code> and <code>NetworkController</code>.
    The <strong>Pages</strong> folder acts as the View, and <code>SnakeGUI.razor</code>
    is responsible for drawing the game and handling user input.
</p>

<h2>Network / Protocol Design</h2>

<p>
    The client connects to the server using the required host and port, sends the player name,
    reads the player ID and world size, then reads wall JSON objects followed by continuous
    snake and power-up updates. The controller identifies each incoming JSON line by checking
    its top-level properties and deserializes it into the correct model object.
</p>

<p>
    The client only sends movement commands after the handshake is complete.
    Supported movement inputs are the default WASD controls required by the assignment.
</p>

<h2>Rendering Design</h2>

<p>
    The game view is drawn on a 1000x1000 canvas. I use world coordinates for all objects
    and translate the drawing context so that the local player's snake head stays centered in
    the viewport. Each frame, the canvas is cleared, the visible region is clipped, the view
    is translated, and then the background, walls, snakes, and power-ups are drawn.
</p>

<p>
    I use different colors for the first several snakes so that different players are visually
    distinguishable. Player names and scores are drawn next to each snake. Wall drawing divides
    walls into 50x50 blocks based on the server-provided endpoints.
</p>

<h2>Features Implemented</h2>

<ul>
    <li>Connect to a server using player name, server address, and port</li>
    <li>Disconnect from the server</li>
    <li>Display the current game world on a 1000x1000 canvas</li>
    <li>Draw walls, snakes, power-ups, player names, and scores</li>
    <li>Center the view on the local player's snake</li>
    <li>Support WASD input for movement commands</li>
    <li>Use separate model, controller, and view responsibilities</li>
</ul>

<h2>Notable Design Decisions</h2>

<ul>
    <li>
        I store the current world state in a <code>World</code> object and protect shared data
        with locking because the networking code updates the world while the GUI reads from it.
    </li>
    <li>
        I deserialize server JSON directly into model objects to keep the networking and model
        code simple and close to the protocol specification.
    </li>
    <li>
        I use an async drawing loop so that drawing operations fit naturally with the async
        canvas API.
    </li>
</ul>

<h2>Current Limitations / Known Issues</h2>

<ul>
    <li>
        Connection failure feedback is currently basic. The GUI reports connection failure, but
        detailed error messages could still be improved.
    </li>
    <li>
        Some polish features such as extra animation effects or crash explosions may still be
        limited or unfinished, depending on the current build.
    </li>
    <li>
        The visual style is functional and readable, but there is still room for more polish.
    </li>
</ul>

<h2>What I Want the Grader to Notice</h2>

<ul>
    <li>The project follows the required MVC organization.</li>
    <li>The client follows the specified connection and communication sequence.</li>
    <li>The game world is rendered in world space with the player's snake centered in view.</li>
    <li>The client supports the required WASD controls and displays player names and scores.</li>
    <li>I focused on making the code readable and keeping responsibilities clearly separated.</li>
</ul>

